etymologies: Middle English: from Old French fel, nominative of felon ‘wicked (person)’ (see felon)

definitions: of terrible evil or ferocity; deadly

examples.text: sorcerers use spells to achieve their fell ends

etymologies: Old English fellan, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch vellen and German fällen, also to fall

definitions: cut down (a tree)

examples.text: 33 million trees are felled each day

definitions: knock down

examples.text: strong winds felled power lines
corruption that felled the financial system in Thailand

definitions: stitch down (the edge of a seam) to lie flat

examples.text: a flat-felled seam

definitions: an amount of timber cut.

etymologies: Middle English: from Old Norse fjall, fell ‘hill’; probably related to German Fels ‘rock’

definitions: a hill or stretch of high moorland, especially in northern England

examples.text: Cross Fell

shortDefinitions: hill or stretch of high moorland

etymologies: Old English fel, fell, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch vel and German Fell, from an Indo-European root shared by Latin pellis and Greek pella ‘skin’

definitions: an animal's hide or skin with its hair.
shortDefinitions: animal's hide or skin with its hair

etymologies: Old English fallan, feallan, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch vallen and German fallen; the noun is partly from the verb, partly from Old Norse fall ‘downfall, sin’

definitions: move downward, typically rapidly and freely without control, from a higher to a lower level

examples.text: five inches of snow fell through the night
bombs could be seen falling from the planes

definitions: hang down

examples.text: hair that was allowed to fall to the shoulders

definitions: (of land) slope downward; drop away

examples.text: the field fell gently downhill

definitions: (of someone's eyes or glance) be directed downward

examples.text: Albert's eyes fell, and he blushed

definitions: (of someone's face) show dismay or disappointment by appearing to sag or droop

examples.text: her face fell as she thought about her life with George

definitions: (of a person) lose one's balance and collapse

examples.text: he stumbled, tripped, and fell

definitions: throw oneself down, typically in order to worship or implore someone

examples.text: they fell on their knees, rendering thanks to God

definitions: (of a tree, building, or other structure) collapse to the ground.
decrease in number, amount, intensity, or quality

examples.text: imports fell by 12 percent
we're worried that standards are falling
temperatures are going to fall to around four degrees

definitions: (of a measuring instrument) show a lower reading

examples.text: the barometer had fallen a further ten points

definitions: be captured or defeated

examples.text: the besieged city fell after three months
their mountain strongholds fell to enemy attack

definitions: die in battle

examples.text: an English leader who had fallen at the hands of the Danes

definitions: (of a government or leader) lose office or be overthrown

examples.text: six months later the government fell as a result of mass strikes

definitions: commit sin; yield to temptation

examples.text: it is their husbands' fault if wives do fall

definitions: pass into a specified state, situation, or position

examples.text: she fell pregnant

definitions: occur or take place

examples.text: when night fell we managed to crawl back to our lines
Mother's birthday fell on Flag Day

definitions: be classified or ordered in the way specified

examples.text: canals fall within the Minister's brief
all that falls under the general heading of corruption
